pressible Women Strike for Peace -- tThe Vietnam Era: The War Against the Peacemakers Berkeley's Free Speech Movement: A Prelude -- tHarassing Antiwar Demonstrator s -- tHUAC, the Police, the FBI, the Courts: Containing an Extraordinary Generation -- tRetribution for Acts of Conscience -- tThe Shootings at Kent State -- tEpilogue: The Heresy of a Modern-Day Social Gospel -- tPART FOUR: PRESERVING THE RIGHT TO DISSENT -- tA Notable Reversal Holding the Chicago Red Squad Accountable -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBud and Ruth Schultz's vivid oral history presents the extraordinary testimony of people who experienced government repression and persecution firsthand. Drawn from three of the most significant social movements of our time--the labor, Black freedom, and antiwar movements--these engrossing interviews bring to life the experiences of Americans who acted upon their beliefs despite the price they paid for their dissent. In doing so, they--and the movements they were part of--helped shape the political and social landscape of the United States from the beginning to the end of the twentieth century.The majority of the voices in this book belong to everyday people--workers, priests, teachers, students--but more well-known figures such as Congressman John Lewis, Kwame Ture (Stokely Carmichael), Abbie Hoffman, and Daniel Ellsberg are also included. There are firsthand accounts by leaders of the Industrial Workers of the World, active early in the century; Southern Tenant Farmers Union of the 1930s; Women's Strike for Peace, the Southern Christian Leadership Conference; the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee; Berkeley's Free Speech Movement of the 1950s and 1960s; and the Hormel meatpackers' Local P-9 in the 1980s. Lively introductions by the authors contextualize these personal statements.Those who tell their stories in The Price of Dissent, and others like them, faced surveillance and disruption from police agencies, such as the FBI; brutalization by local police; local ordinances and court injunctions limiting protest; inquisitions into beliefs and associations by congressional committees; prosecution under laws that curbed dissent; denaturalization and deportation; and purges under government loyalty programs. Agree with them or not, by dissenting when it was unpopular or dangerous to do so, they insisted on exercising the precious American right of free expression and preserved it for a new century's dissenters.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical persecutionzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 4aUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aBaden, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBass, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Norma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCain, Cecil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanfora, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanfora, Rosseann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Jake, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeboer, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemaio, Ernest, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDymally, Mervyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllsberg, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Jackie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrossman, Mildred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v